[_Mycobacterium ulcerans_ infections have been historically restricted to
geographic pockets in Southeast Asia, Australia, Africa and Mexico, often
swampy areas. The organism differs from many _Mycobacterium_ sp. insofar
as it seldom causes granulomatous lesions. Disease begins as a nodular
lesion that progresses to a chronic, necrotizing skin ulcer, generally more
superficial than is characteristic of leprosy. Therapy has been difficult.
It should be remembered that the emergence of this disease is superimposed
on an incidence of HIV infection that approximates 25% in adult populations
in some parts of Africa. Comments from those with direct microbiological
and clinical experience would be helpful. - Mod.ES
